In the Java/C# world, DI containers are a religion.
In Node.js, most developers just import modules directly, until testing bec=
omes a nightmare and swapping implementations means rewriting half the app.
You don=E2=80=99t need dependency injection containers like InversifyJS [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/92431213-07a1-46d6-a788-4675ac1acbf8?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiMTNlanV2In0.TRwTjGQpT3mmoffvWguYKhmiXfEGLhcrUpphZJdWS0w ] or tsyringe [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/05dcb0df-f114-446f-815e-a54e184701de?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiMTNlanV2In0.TRwTjGQpT3mmoffvWguYKhmiXfEGLhcrUpphZJdWS0w ].
Here=E2=80=99s how to do dependency injection with plain TypeScript, and wh=
y it=E2=80=99ll make your code instantly more testable.
Dependency Injection vs. Dependency Inversion
These terms get used interchangeably. But they're not the same.
Dependency Injection (DI) is a technique: instead of a class/function creat=
ing its own dependencies, you pass them in from the outside.
Dependency Inversion is a principle (the =E2=80=9CD=E2=80=9D in SOLID): hig=
h-level modules shouldn=E2=80=99t depend on low-level modules. Both should =
depend on abstractions.
Dependency Injection is how you implement Dependency Inversion.
But you can do DI without inverting anything. This is the place where most =
Node.js developers stop.
// Direct dependency =E2=80=94 no injection
import { db } from './database';

export async function getUser(id: string) {
  return db.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE id =3D $1', [id]);
}
This works. But you can=E2=80=99t test getUser without a real database.
You can=E2=80=99t swap PostgreSQL for an in-memory store.
And if database.ts has side effects on import, every test file that touches=
 getUser pays that cost.
The Node.js Anti-Pattern: Import Everything Directly
Here=E2=80=99s what most Express apps look like:
// userService.ts
import { knex } from =E2=80=98../lib/database=E2=80=99;
import { sendEmail } from =E2=80=98../lib/email=E2=80=99;
import { logger } from =E2=80=98../lib/logger=E2=80=99;

export async function createUser(data: CreateUserInput) {
  const [user] =3D await knex(=E2=80=99users=E2=80=99).insert(data).returni=
ng(=E2=80=99*=E2=80=99);
  await sendEmail(user.email, =E2=80=98Welcome!=E2=80=99);
  logger.info(`User created: ${user.id}`);
  return user;
}
There are three hardcoded dependencies. And to test this function, you need=
:
A running database (or mock Knex globally)
An email service (or mock the module)
A logger (or suppress output)
Module mocking (jest.mock, vi.mock) is the usual escape hatch, but it=E2=80=
=99s brittle because we=E2=80=99re mocking import paths, not the actual con=
tracts.
For example, if you rename a file, your mocks break silently.
Module mocking is a code smell.
It tells you your code has hidden dependencies that should be explicit.
What Dependency Injection Actually Solves
Before we continue further, let=E2=80=99s be clear about what we=E2=80=99re=
 fixing:
Testability. When a module imports its dependencies directly, you=E2=80=99r=
e forced into module-level mocking (jest.mock(), vi.mock()) to test it. The=
se mocks are fragile, magical, and break when you rename a file. With DI, y=
ou pass plain objects, and no mocking framework is needed.
Swappability. Imagine you have to switch from Knex to Drizzle, or from Send=
Grid to AWS SES. When dependencies are injected, you swap the implementatio=
n in one place. When they=E2=80=99re imported, you touch every file.
Explicit dependencies. A function=E2=80=99s signature should tell you what =
it needs. If createUser secretly depends on a database, an email client, an=
d a logger, but its signature only shows data: CreateUserDTO, that=E2=80=99=
s a lie. DI makes dependencies visible.
Separation of concerns. Your business logic shouldn=E2=80=99t know (or care=
) whether it=E2=80=99s talking to Postgres or SQLite, SendGrid or a local S=
MTP server. DI enforces that boundary naturally.
Now, let=E2=80=99s see how to do dependency injection in Node.js without an=
y frameworks.
