Step 1: Constructor Injection (Manual DI)
The simplest fix: accept dependencies as parameters.
// userService.ts
interface UserRepository {
  create(data: CreateUserInput): Promise<User>;
}

interface EmailService {
  send(to: string, subject: string): Promise<void>;
}

interface Logger {
  info(message: string): void;
}

export function createUserService(
  repo: UserRepository,
  email: EmailService,
  logger: Logger
) {
  return {
    async createUser(data: CreateUserInput) {
      const user =3D await repo.create(data);
      await email.send(user.email, =E2=80=98Welcome!=E2=80=99);
      logger.info(`User created: ${user.id}`);
      return user;
    },
  };
}
Before and After DI: How You Use the Code
The real difference isn=E2=80=99t just how the service is defined, but how =
it=E2=80=99s consumed.
Before DI, we use direct imports (hidden dependencies):
// Somewhere in your route handler or controller
import { createUser } from =E2=80=98./userService=E2=80=99;

// Just call it. What does it need? Who knows.
// Knex? Email service? Logger? You can=E2=80=99t tell from here.
const user =3D await createUser({ email: =E2=80=98alice@example.com=E2=80=
=99, name: =E2=80=98Alice=E2=80=99 });
Dependencies are invisible.
The function looks simple, but it=E2=80=99s secretly reaching into the modu=
le graph for a database client, an email service, and a logger.
You only discover this when something breaks or when you try to test it.
After DI, we use Factory + DI (explicit dependencies):
// In your composition root or setup code
import { createUserService } from =E2=80=98./userService=E2=80=99;
import { createUserRepo } from =E2=80=98./repos/userRepo=E2=80=99;
import { createEmailService } from =E2=80=98./infra/email=E2=80=99;
import { createLogger } from =E2=80=98./infra/logger=E2=80=99;

// Dependencies are explicit at creation time
const userService =3D createUserService(
  createUserRepo(knex),
  createEmailService({ apiKey: process.env.SENDGRID_KEY! }),
  createLogger({ level: =E2=80=98info=E2=80=99 })
);

// Now use it =E2=80=94 the service is fully configured
const user =3D await userService.createUser({ email: =E2=80=98alice@example=
=2Ecom=E2=80=99, name: =E2=80=98Alice=E2=80=99 });
Yes, the setup is more verbose. But now you can see every dependency. The f=
unction signature tells the truth.
When you read the composition root, you know exactly what each service need=
s, no grepping through imports, no surprises.
Step 2: The Composition Root=20
If every service takes its dependencies as arguments, where do you actually=
 wire everything together?
At the composition root, the entry point of your application. This is the o=
ne place that knows about all the concrete implementations.
// composition-root.ts
import Knex from =E2=80=98knex=E2=80=99;
import { createKnexDatabase } from =E2=80=98./infra/knexDatabase=E2=80=99;
import { createUserService } from =E2=80=98./services/userService=E2=80=99;
import { createOrderService } from =E2=80=98./services/orderService=E2=80=
=99;
import { createEmailService } from =E2=80=98./infra/email=E2=80=99;
import { createLogger } from =E2=80=98./infra/logger=E2=80=99;

export function createApp() {
  // Infrastructure
  const knex =3D Knex({
    client: =E2=80=98pg=E2=80=99,
    connection: process.env.DATABASE_URL,
  });
  const db =3D createKnexDatabase(knex);
  const email =3D createEmailService({ apiKey: process.env.SENDGRID_KEY! })=
;
  const logger =3D createLogger({ level: =E2=80=98info=E2=80=99 });

  // Repositories
  const userRepo =3D createUserRepo(db);
  const orderRepo =3D createOrderRepo(db);

  // Services
  const userService =3D createUserService(userRepo, email, logger);
  const orderService =3D createOrderService(orderRepo, userService, logger)=
;

  return { userService, orderService, knex };
}
// server.ts
import express from =E2=80=98express=E2=80=99;
import { createApp } from =E2=80=98./composition-root=E2=80=99;

const app =3D express();
const { userService, orderService } =3D createApp();

app.post(=E2=80=99/users=E2=80=99, async (req, res) =3D> {
  const user =3D await userService.createUser(req.body);
  res.status(201).json(user);
});
Everything flows downward from one place. No global singletons. No magical =
auto-wiring. Just functions calling functions.
When to Reach for a Container?
Manual DI works beautifully for small-to-medium apps.
But when you have 20-30+ services with complex dependency graphs, the compo=
sition root becomes hard to read and follow.
I=E2=80=99ve personally used tsyringe [ https://substack.com/redirect/05dcb=
0df-f114-446f-815e-a54e184701de?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMTNlanV2In0.TRwTjGQpT3mmoffvWgu=
YKhmiXfEGLhcrUpphZJdWS0w ]. It=E2=80=99s a lightweight container, easy to u=
se and configure.
tsyringe [ https://substack.com/redirect/05dcb0df-f114-446f-815e-a54e184701=
de?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMTNlanV2In0.TRwTjGQpT3mmoffvWguYKhmiXfEGLhcrUpphZJdWS0w ] us=
es decorators and reflect-metadata to inspect constructor parameters and au=
to-wire dependencies.
It supports singleton, transient, and scoped lifecycles, with strong TypeSc=
ript support.
To be honest, I didn=E2=80=99t have any trouble with it.
Here is a simple example:
import =E2=80=98reflect-metadata=E2=80=99;
import { container, injectable, inject, singleton } from =E2=80=98tsyringe=
=E2=80=99;
import Knex from =E2=80=98knex=E2=80=99;

@singleton()
class KnexDatabase implements Database {
  private knex =3D Knex({ client: =E2=80=98pg=E2=80=99, connection: process=
=2Eenv.DATABASE_URL });

  users =3D {
    create: async (data: CreateUserInput) =3D> {
      const [user] =3D await this.knex(=E2=80=99users=E2=80=99).insert(data=
).returning(=E2=80=99*=E2=80=99);
      return user;
    },
    findById: async (id: string) =3D> {
      return this.knex(=E2=80=99users=E2=80=99).where({ id }).first() ?? nu=
ll;
    },
  };
}

container.register(=E2=80=99Database=E2=80=99, { useClass: KnexDatabase });

@injectable()
class UserService {
  constructor(@inject(=E2=80=99Database=E2=80=99) private db: Database) {}

  async createUser(data: CreateUserInput) {
    return this.db.users.create(data);
  }
}

// Resolve with all dependencies auto-wired
const userService =3D container.resolve(UserService);
If you=E2=80=99re not sure whether you need a container, start simple witho=
ut an additional framework.
You can easily add it later if needed.
The Testing Payoff
Here=E2=80=99s why all this matters. Let=E2=80=99s compare full test files =
side by side.
Before: Testing with Module Mocking
import { describe, it, expect, vi, beforeEach } from =E2=80=98vitest=E2=80=
=99;

// Mock every dependency by file path =E2=80=94 get any path wrong and it s=
ilently breaks
vi.mock(=E2=80=99../lib/database=E2=80=99, () =3D> ({
  knex: vi.fn().mockReturnValue({
    insert: vi.fn().mockReturnValue({
