The difference:
No mocking framework required: plain objects that match the interface
Type-safe: TypeScript checks your fakes against the real interfaces
No import order tricks: just functions and objects
Portable: works with Vitest, Jest, Node=E2=80=99s test runner, or even a pl=
ain script
Each test is self-contained: no shared mutable mock state leaks between tes=
ts
=F0=9F=93=8C Key Takeaways
Dependency Injection isn=E2=80=99t a framework feature =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=
=99s passing arguments to functions. You already know how to do it.
Module mocking is a smell. If you need vi.mock() to test something, remembe=
r that something has hidden dependencies.
Start with manual DI. Factory functions + a composition root covers 90% of =
Node.js apps.
Graduate to a container (tsyringe) when your dependency graph gets complex.=
 Not because it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cproper=E2=80=9D, but because it saves ma=
intenance.
The real value is testability. DI makes unit testing trivial, integration t=
esting focused, and your architecture honest about its dependencies.
